title: For Sale:  SKS Russian Sneak
postcontent:
This is a gun with a neat history. This is a Russian SKS, built between 1952-1954. In the late 50s, the Russians sent their surplus SKS's to aid the Chinese. The Chinese would remove the receiver cover (the main part identifying the gun as Russian), and put on one of their Chinese SKS receiver covers. At another point in time, the Chinese sent a bunch of SKS's to aid Albania, which would be a mix of Chinese guns and some of these Russian guns. The Albanians made their own replacement stocks for the SKS which are unique. Fast forward to 2010 and 2012... the last two major shipments of Chinese guns imported into the US came out of Albania. Russian guns, which had long been banned from import to the US, were mixed in with these Chinese guns and import stamped Chinese, and brought into the US. We call them sneaks, because they "snuck" into the country mixed with Chinese guns.

My particular Russian fits right into that known scenario. It is all numbers matching except for the Chinese receiver cover, and Albanian stock. What's nice about Russian sneaks, is that they are not refurbished like 95% of all other Russian SKS's were.

Asking $475 or best offer. I will ship to your FFL.

title: For Sale:  Colt AR15 A3 Tactical (6721) w/ Troy Industries Quad Rail
location: St. Charles County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Excellent condition Colt Defense 6721 (also designated AR15 A3 Tactical) in 5.56/.223.  This is the heavy barreled version (designated as "HBAR" on the barrel) of the venerable Colt 6920.  The other difference between the 6721 and the 6920 lies in the barrel twist rate which is 1/9, vs. the 1/7 twist rate of the Colt 6920.  1/9 twist is optimal for bullet weights up to 69 grains (which is the vast majority of bullet weights commercially available).  These rifles are renowned for their superb accuracy and combat reliability.  

This carbine is chambered in 5.56/.223, and is outfitted with a Troy Industries quad rail (which allows for attachment of tactical lights, fore grips, etc.), Rock River Arms Dominator rear sight/EOTech mount (instead of the plastic Magpul rear sight), and Knights Armament vertical fore grip.  The quad rail is outfitted with Magpul rail covers that can be easily removed.  The rifle and everything on it are in excellent condition.  Rifle has had LESS than 50 rounds fired through it for zeroing and function checking purposes.  It was then PROPERLY cleaned, lubricated, and put in a safe where it has stayed since then.  

If you've researched the AR-15 platform at all, then you know Colt is the gold standard of AR-15s.  If you want something to just plink at the range with, then to to Wal Mart and buy the cheapest AR you can find.  If you a rifle that is built for combat and reliability, buy a Colt, and you will not find a Colt AR-15 with these options and in this condition for a better price.  Sale of this rifle will include several boxes of match grade .223 ammo.  

Email or text REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  1943 Soviet TT-33 Tokarev Pistol NO ADDED SAFETY WW2
location: South Bay L.A., Redondo Beach and adjacent, Los Angeles, California
postcontent:
This  Soviet WW2 Tokarev pistol is chambered in 7.62x25 Tokarev, and in hard-to-find unaltered condition.

1943 dated, matching frame, barrel, and magazine serial #s.  The magazine has the original number struck out, and the same original number restruck at rebuild, so yes, it's the original mag, that's just the way the rebuild factory did it.

Iznevsk arsenal (arrow in a triangle) marked.

This Tok has NO ADDED SAFETY.  Most of these in the US had an added safety to meet import requirements, originals like this without the safety are hard to find.
The hammer has a half cock position, which is the original safety feature of this gun.

Original  Soviet bakelite grips marked with a star, surrounded by "CCCP", which I believer are initials for the Cyrillic spelling of SojÃºz SovÃ©tskix SocialistÃ­ceskix RespÃºblik.

Rearsenal marked (square with a slash through it).

Import marked "TG IMP WPG FLA" on underside of the frame.

The TT-33, developed by Feodor V. Tokarev, an improvement over his previous TT30, was based on John Browning's pistol designs.  Firing the 7.62X25 bottleneck cartridge, this Red Army pistol replaced the Soviet's Nagant M1895 revolver series.  It was replaced by the Makarov pistol around 1952.


TT's saw extensive combat service in World War 2 (including the Russo-Finnish War), the Korean War, the Chinese Civil War and the Vietnam War, and undoubtedly others as well.  

This short recoil actuated, locked breech, single action Tok weighs about 30 ounces unloaded, overall length is about 7.6 inches, with a 4.6 inch barrel. 

For FTF sale at a local FFL.  All laws apply, thanks for looking!

$1,200

title: For Sale:  Bulgarian Makarov  SOLD SOLD
location: South Bay L.A., Redondo Beach and adj., Los Angeles, California
postcontent:
SOLD, thanks Armslist    Bulgarian circle 10 military Makarov in very good condition, chambered in 9x18mm, imported by PW Arms Redmond WA.
This is a nice little beauty, great CCW weapon.

For FTF PPT sale at a local FFL in the South Bay L.A. area.

Frame and slide are stamped matching, the two 8 round mags are electropencil matching.


The Makarov was developed by Soviets from German technology, in this case the Walther PP/PPK. 


While the PM resembles the Walther PP and has a similar operating system, there are some notable differences, especially in the safety. The Walther employs a hammer-drop safety that may be set before the slide is operated to allow the hammer to ride forward as the slide returns to the closed position, or it may be operated after a round is chambered. 

The Makarov safety/hammer drop operates in reverse of that of the Walther. While the safety is pressed downward to drop the hammer on a Walther, on the Makarov it is pressed upward. Also, when the Makarov safety is in the up position, it locks the action. In order to enable the double action of the Makarov, the safety must be returned to the down position after using it to drop the hammer.
